# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: stable-roommates
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The **assignment problem** is a fundamental combinatorial optimization problem.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] that may vary depending on the agent-task assignment.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] of maximum size, in which the sum of weights of the edges is minimum.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] If the numbers of agents and tasks are equal, then the problem is called **balanced assignment**, and the graph-theoretic version is called **minimum-cost perfect matching**.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Otherwise, it is called **unbalanced assignment**.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] If the total cost of the assignment for all tasks is equal to the sum of the costs for each agent (or the sum of the costs for each task, which is the same thing in this case), then the problem is called **linear assignment**.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Commonly, when speaking of the *assignment problem* without any additional qualification, then the *linear balanced assignment problem* is meant.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Suppose that a taxi firm has three taxis (the agents) available, and three customers (the tasks) wishing to be picked up as soon as possible.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The firm prides itself on speedy pickups, so for each taxi the "cost" of picking up a particular customer will depend on the time taken for the taxi to reach the pickup point.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] This is a *balanced assignment* problem.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Its solution is whichever combination of taxis and customers results in the least total cost.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Now, suppose that there are *four* taxis available, but still only three customers.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] This is an *unbalanced assignment* problem.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] One way to solve it is to invent a fourth dummy task, perhaps called "sitting still doing nothing", with a cost of 0 for the taxi assigned to it.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] This reduces the problem to a balanced assignment problem, which can then be solved in the usual way and still give the best solution to the problem.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Similar adjustments can be done in order to allow more tasks than agents, tasks to which multiple agents must be assigned (for instance, a group of more customers than will fit in one taxi), or maximizing profit rather than minimizing cost.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The problem is "linear" because the cost function to be optimized as well as all the constraints contain only linear terms.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] A naive solution for the assignment problem is to check all the assignments and calculate the cost of each one.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] This may be very inefficient since, with *n* agents and *n* tasks, there are *n*!
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] (factorial of *n*) different assignments.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Another naive solution is to greedily assign the pair with the smallest cost first, and remove the vertices; then, among the remaining vertices, assign the pair with the smallest cost; and so on.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] This algorithm may yield a non-optimal solution.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The greedy algorithm would assign Task 1 to Alice and Task 2 to George, for a total cost of 9, but the reverse assignment has a total cost of 7.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Fortunately, there are many algorithms for finding the optimal assignment in time polynomial in *n*.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The assignment problem is a special case of the transportation problem, which is a special case of the minimum cost flow problem, which in turn is a special case of a linear program.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] While it is possible to solve any of these problems using the simplex algorithm, or in worst-case polynomial time using the ellipsoid method, each specialization has a smaller solution space and thus more efficient algorithms designed to take advantage of its special structure.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] In the balanced assignment problem, both parts of the bipartite graph have the same number of vertices, denoted by *n*.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] One of the first polynomial-time algorithms for balanced assignment was the Hungarian algorithm.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] It is a *global* algorithm – it is based on improving a matching along augmenting paths (alternating paths between unmatched vertices).
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Its run-time complexity, when using Fibonacci heaps, is $O(mn+n^{2}\log n)$ , where *m* is the number of edges.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] This is currently the fastest run-time of a strongly polynomial algorithm for this problem.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Some variants of the Hungarian algorithm also benefit from parallel computing, including GPU acceleration.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] If all weights are integers, then the run-time can be improved to $O(mn+n^{2}\log \log n)$ , but the resulting algorithm is only weakly polynomial.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] If the weights are integers, and all weights are at most *C* (where *C*>1 is some integer), then the problem can be solved in $O(m{\sqrt {n}}\log(n\cdot C))$ weakly-polynomial time in a method called *weight scaling*.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] In addition to the global methods, there are *local methods* which are based on finding local updates (rather than full augmenting paths).
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] These methods have worse asymptotic runtime guarantees, but they often work better in practice.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] These algorithms are called auction algorithms, push-relabel algorithms, or preflow-push algorithms.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Some of these algorithms were shown to be equivalent.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Some of the local methods assume that the graph admits a *perfect matching*; if this is not the case, then some of these methods might run forever.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] A simple technical way to solve this problem is to extend the input graph to a *complete bipartite graph,* by adding artificial edges with very large weights.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] These weights should exceed the weights of all existing matchings, to prevent appearance of artificial edges in the possible solution.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] As shown by Mulmuley, Vazirani and Vazirani, the problem of minimum weight perfect matching is converted to finding minors in the adjacency matrix of a graph.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Using the isolation lemma, a minimum weight perfect matching in a graph can be found with probability at least 1⁄2.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] For a graph with *n* vertices, it requires $O(\log ^{2}(n))$ time.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] In the unbalanced assignment problem, the larger part of the bipartite graph has *n* vertices and the smaller part has *r*<*n* vertices.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] There is also a constant *s* which is at most the cardinality of a maximum matching in the graph.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The goal is to find a minimum-cost matching of size exactly *s*.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The most common case is the case in which the graph admits a one-sided-perfect matching (i.e., a matching of size *r*), and *s*=*r*.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Unbalanced assignment can be reduced to a balanced assignment.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The naive reduction is to add $n-r$ new vertices to the smaller part and connect them to the larger part using edges of cost 0.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] However, this requires $n(n-r)$ new edges.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] A more efficient reduction is called the *doubling technique*.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Here, a new graph *G'* is built from two copies of the original graph *G*: a forward copy *Gf* and a backward copy *Gb.* The backward copy is "flipped", so that, in each side of *G'*, there are now *n*+*r* vertices.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] All in all, at most $n+r$ new edges are required.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The resulting graph always has a perfect matching of size $n+r$ .
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] A minimum-cost perfect matching in this graph must consist of minimum-cost maximum-cardinality matchings in *Gf* and *Gb.* The main problem with this doubling technique is that there is no speed gain when $r\ll n$ .
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Instead of using reduction, the unbalanced assignment problem can be solved by directly generalizing existing algorithms for balanced assignment.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The Hungarian algorithm can be generalized to solve the problem in $O(ms+s^{2}\log r)$ strongly-polynomial time.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] In particular, if *s*=*r* then the runtime is $O(mr+r^{2}\log r)$ .
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] If the weights are integers, then Thorup's method can be used to get a runtime of $O(ms+s^{2}\log \log r)$ .
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The assignment problem can be solved by presenting it as a linear program.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] For convenience we will present the maximization problem.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Each edge (*i*,*j*), where *i* is in A and *j* is in T, has a weight ${\textstyle w_{ij}}$ .
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] For each edge ⁠ $(i,j)$ ⁠ we have a variable ${\textstyle x_{ij}}$ .
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The total weight of the matching is: $\sum _{(i,j)\in A\times T}w_{ij}x_{ij}$ .
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The goal is to find a maximum-weight perfect matching.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] However, we can solve it without the integrality constraints (i.e., drop the last constraint), using standard methods for solving continuous linear programs.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] While this formulation allows also fractional variable values, in this special case, the LP always has an optimal solution where the variables take integer values.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] This is because the constraint matrix of the fractional LP is totally unimodular – it satisfies the four conditions of Hoffman and Gale.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Other approaches for the assignment problem exist and are reviewed by Duan and Pettie (see Table II).
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Their work proposes an approximation algorithm for the assignment problem (and the more general maximum-weight matching problem), which runs in linear time for any fixed error bound.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] In the basic assignment problem, each agent is assigned to at most one task and each task is assigned to at most one agent.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] In the **many-to-many assignment problem**, each agent *i* may take up to *ci* tasks (*ci* is called the agent's *capacity*), and each task *j* may be taken by up to *dj* agents simultaneously (*dj* is called the task's *capacity*).
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] If the sums of capacities in both sides are equal ( $\sum _{i}c_{i}=\sum _{j}d_{j}$ ), then the problem is *balanced*, and the goal is to find a perfect matching (assign exactly *ci* tasks to each agent *i* and exactly *dj* agents to each task *j*) such that the total cost is as small as possible.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The problem can be solved by reduction to the minimum cost network flow problem.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] An integral maximum flow of minimum cost can be found in polynomial time; see network flow problem.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Every integral maximum flow in this network corresponds to a matching in which at most *ci* tasks are assigned to each agent *i* and at most *dj* agents are assigned to each task *j* (in the balanced case, exactly *ci* tasks are assigned to *i* and exactly *dj* agents are assigned to *j*).
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] A min-cost maximum flow corresponds to a min-cost assignment.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] When phrased as a graph theory problem, the assignment problem can be extended from bipartite graphs to arbitrary graphs.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] The corresponding problem, of finding a matching in a weighted graph where the sum of weights is maximized, is called the maximum-weight matching problem.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] Another generalization of the assignment problem is extending the number of sets to be matched from two to many.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] So that rather than matching agents to tasks, the problem is extended to matching agents to tasks to time intervals to locations.
[src:stable-roommates/assignment-problem] This results in Multidimensional assignment problem.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] In mathematics, economics, and computer science, the **Gale–Shapley algorithm** (also known as the **deferred acceptance algorithm**, **propose-and-reject algorithm**, or **Boston Pool algorithm**) is an algorithm for finding a solution to the stable matching problem.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] It is named for David Gale and Lloyd Shapley, who published it in 1962, although it had been used for the National Resident Matching Program since the early 1950s.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Roth (who pointed out its prior application) won the 2012 Nobel Prize in Economics for work including this algorithm.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] The stable matching problem seeks to pair up equal numbers of participants of two types, using preferences from each participant.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] The pairing must be stable: no pair of matched participants should mutually prefer each other to their assigned match.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] In each round of the Gale–Shapley algorithm, unmatched participants of one type propose a match to the next participant on their preference list.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Each proposal is accepted if its recipient prefers it to their current match.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] The resulting procedure is a truthful mechanism from the point of view of the proposing participants, who receive their most-preferred pairing consistent with stability.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] In contrast, the recipients of proposals receive their least-preferred pairing.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] The algorithm can be implemented to run in time quadratic in the number of participants, and linear in the size of the input to the algorithm.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] The stable matching problem, and the Gale–Shapley algorithm solving it, have widespread real-world applications, including matching American medical students to residencies and French university applicants to schools.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] For more, see Stable marriage problem § Applications.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] The stable matching problem, in its most basic form, takes as input equal numbers of two types of participants (n job applicants and n employers, for example), and an ordering for each participant giving their preference for whom to be matched to among the participants of the other type.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] A matching pairs each participant of one type with a participant of the other type.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] *B* also prefers *A* over the element to which *B* is already matched.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] In other words, a matching is stable when there is no pair (*A*, *B*) where both participants prefer each other to their matched partners.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] If such a pair exists, the matching is not stable, in the sense that the members of this pair would prefer to leave the system and be matched to each other, possibly leaving other participants unmatched.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] A stable matching always exists, and the algorithmic problem solved by the Gale–Shapley algorithm is to find one.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] The stable matching problem has also been called the *stable marriage problem*, using a metaphor of marriage between men and women, and many sources describe the Gale–Shapley algorithm in terms of marriage proposals.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] However, this metaphor has been criticized as both sexist and unrealistic: the steps of the algorithm do not accurately reflect typical or even stereotypical human behavior.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] In 1962, David Gale and Lloyd Shapley proved that, for any equal number of participants of each type, it is always possible to find a matching in which all pairs are stable.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Roth observed that essentially the same algorithm had already been in practical use since the early 1950s, as the "Boston Pool algorithm" used by the National Resident Matching Program.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] The Gale–Shapley algorithm involves a number of "rounds" (or "iterations").
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] To implement the algorithm efficiently, each employer needs to be able to find its next applicant quickly, and each applicant needs to be able to compare employers quickly.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Setting up these data structures takes $O(n^{2})$ time.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] With these structures it is possible to find an employer with an unfilled position, make an offer from that employer to their next applicant, determine whether the offer is accepted, and update all of the data structures to reflect the results of these steps, in constant time per offer.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Once the algorithm terminates, the resulting matching can be read off from the array of employers for each applicant.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] There can be $O(n^{2})$ offers before each employer runs out of offers to make, so the total time is $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Although this time bound is quadratic in the number of participants, it may be considered as linear time when measured in terms of the size of the input, two matrices of preferences of size $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] At the end, there cannot be an applicant and employer both unmatched.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] An employer left unmatched at the end of the process must have made an offer to all applicants.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] But an applicant who receives an offer remains employed for the rest of the process, so there can be no unemployed applicants.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Since the numbers of applicants and job openings are equal, there can also be no open positions remaining.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] can prefer each other over their final match.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] There may be many stable matchings for the same system of preferences.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] This raises the question: which matching is returned by the Gale–Shapley algorithm?
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Is it the matching better for applicants, for employers, or an intermediate one?
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] In a reversed form of the algorithm, each round consists of unemployed applicants writing a single job application to their preferred employer, and the employer either accepting the application (possibly firing an existing employee to do so) or rejecting it.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] This produces a matching that is best for all applicants and worst for all employers among all stable matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] These two matchings are the top and bottom elements of the lattice of stable matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] In both forms of the algorithm, one group of participants proposes matches, and the other group decides whether to accept or reject each proposal.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] The matching is always best for the group that makes the propositions, and worst for the group that decides how to handle each proposal.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] The Gale–Shapley algorithm is a truthful mechanism from the point of view of the proposing side.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] This means that no proposer can get a better matching by misrepresenting their preferences.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Moreover, the Gale–Shapley algorithm is even *group-strategy proof* for proposers, i.e., no coalition of proposers can coordinate a misrepresentation of their preferences such that all proposers in the coalition are strictly better-off.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] However, it is possible for some coalition to misrepresent their preferences such that some proposers are better-off, and the others retain the same partner.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] The Gale–Shapley algorithm is non-truthful for the non-proposing participants.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Each may be able to misrepresent their preferences and get a better match.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] A particular form of manipulation is *truncation*: presenting only the topmost alternatives, implying that the bottom alternatives are not acceptable at all.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Under complete information, it is sufficient to consider misrepresentations of the form of truncation strategies.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] However, successful misrepresentation requires knowledge of the other agents' preferences; without such knowledge, misrepresentation can give an agent a worse assignment.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Moreover, even after an agent sees the final matching, they cannot deduce a strategy that would guarantee a better outcome in hindsight.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] This makes the Gale–Shapley algorithm a *regret-free truth-telling mechanism*.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Moreover, in the Gale–Shapley algorithm, truth-telling is the only strategy that guarantees no regret.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] The Gale–Shapley algorithm is the only regret-free mechanism in the class of quantile-stable matching mechanisms.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] In their original work on the problem, Gale and Shapley considered a more general form of the stable matching problem, suitable for university and college admission.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] In this problem, each university or college may have its own *quota*, a target number of students to admit, and the number of students applying for admission may differ from the sum of the quotas, necessarily causing either some students to remain unmatched or some quotas to remain unfilled.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Nevertheless, it is possible to define stable matchings for this more general problem, to prove that stable matchings always exist, and to apply the same algorithm to find one.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] A form of the Gale–Shapley algorithm, performed through a real-world protocol rather than calculated on computers, has been used for coordinating higher education admissions in France since 2018, through the Parcoursup system.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] In this process, over the course of the summer before the start of school, applicants receive offers of admission, and must choose in each round of the process whether to accept any new offer (and if so turn down any previous offer that they accepted).
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] The method is complicated by additional constraints that make the problem it solves not exactly the stable matching problem.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] It has the advantage that the students do not need to commit to their preferences at the start of the process, but rather can determine their own preferences as the algorithm progresses, on the basis of head-to-head comparisons between offers that they have received.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] It is important that this process performs a small number of rounds of proposals, so that it terminates before the start date of the schools, but although high numbers of rounds can occur in theory, they tend not to occur in practice.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] It has been shown theoretically that, if the Gale–Shapley algorithm needs to be terminated early, after a small number of rounds in which every vacant position makes a new offer, it nevertheless produces matchings that have a high ratio of matched participants to unstable pairs.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] The Gale–Shapley algorithm has a natural source of parallelism that makes it suitable for parallel hardware such as multicore CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] In each round, all employers with unfilled positions can independently advance along their preference lists and make offers concurrently.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] A parallel implementation can assign threads to independent employers so that many offers are made simultaneously.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] When multiple employers make offers to the same applicant, synchronization primitives are used to resolve the competing offers, ensuring that only the applicant’s most-preferred employer is tentatively accepted while the rejected employers continue to their next choices.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] To reduce synchronization overhead, it is advantageous to avoid repeatedly returning rejected employers to the shared set of employers with unfilled positions, since concurrent updates to this set require synchronization.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Instead, a rejected employer immediately continues to the next applicant on its preference list.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] If an applicant accepts a new offer, the displaced employer likewise continues from its next preference.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Heterogeneous approaches further improve performance by using the GPU for highly parallel stages and switching to the CPU when few employers remain unmatched, avoiding GPU underutilization during mostly sequential work.
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Shapley and Roth were awarded the 2012 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences "for the theory of stable allocations and the practice of market design".
[src:stable-roommates/gale-shapley-algorithm] Gale had died in 2008, making him ineligible for the prize.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] In mathematics, economics, and computer science, a **lattice of stable matchings** is a distributive lattice whose elements are all the solutions to a given instance of the stable matching problem.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] These solutions, called *stable matchings*, pair up participants of two types in such a way that no two participants would prefer to be paired with each other than to accept their assigned pairings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Being a lattice means that, for a comparison operation between stable matchings based on the preferences of the participants, each two stable matchings have a unique greatest lower bound and a unique least upper bound.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Together, the greatest lower bound and least upper bound operations obey the distributive law.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] This structure was originally described in the 1970s by John Horton Conway and Donald Knuth.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The Gale–Shapley algorithm can find either of two special stable matchings, the greatest and least matchings in the lattice.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The entire lattice has a concise representation that can be constructed in polynomial time, by using Birkhoff's representation theorem to describe it as the family of lower sets of an underlying partially ordered set.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The elements of this partially ordered set are called rotations; they are cycle graphs that describe the symmetric difference between two stable matchings that are adjacent in the lattice.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Algorithms that operate on this partial order instead of directly on stable matchings, and that search for lower sets that are optimal in some way, can find in polynomial time the minimum or maximum weight stable matching, for weighted instances of the stable matching problem.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Every finite distributive lattice can be represented as a lattice of stable matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The number of matchings in the lattice can vary from an average case of $e^{-1}n\ln n$ to a worst case of exponential, where n is the number of participants of each kind to be matched.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Computing the number of stable matchings for a given instance of stable matching is #P-complete.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] In its simplest form, an instance of the stable matching problem consists of two equal-sized finite sets of participants to be matched to each other, for instance doctors seeking jobs and hospitals seeking to hire a doctor.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The goal is to find a matching that is *stable*: no pair of a doctor and a hospital prefer each other to their assigned match.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Versions of this problem are used, for instance, by the National Resident Matching Program to match American medical students to hospitals.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] In general, there may be many different stable matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] All participants get their second choice: AX, BY, CZ.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The hospitals get their first choice and the doctors their third: AZ, BX, CY.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The lattice of stable matchings organizes this collection of solutions, for any instance of stable matching, giving it the structure of a distributive lattice.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The lattice of stable matchings is based on the following weaker structure, a partially ordered set whose elements are the stable matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Define a comparison operation $\leq$ on the stable matchings, where $P\leq Q$ if and only if all doctors prefer matching Q to matching P : either they have the same assigned hospital in both matchings, or they are assigned a better hospital in Q than they are in P .
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] If the doctors disagree on which matching they prefer, then P and Q are incomparable: neither one is $\leq$ the other.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The same comparison operation can be defined in the same way for any two sets of participants to be matched, not just doctors and hospitals.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The choice of which of the two sets of participants to use in the role of the doctors is arbitrary.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Swapping the roles of the doctors and hospitals reverses the ordering of every pair of stable matchings, but does not otherwise change the structure of the partial order.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] This ordering gives the matchings the structure of a partially ordered set.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] For stable matchings, all three properties follow directly from the definition of the comparison operation.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Define the best match of a participant x of a stable matching instance to be the participant y that x most prefers, among all the participants for which there exists a stable matching that pairs x with y , and define the worst match analogously.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Then no two participants can have the same best match.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] For, suppose to the contrary that doctors x and $x'$ both have y as their best match, and that y prefers x to $x'$ .
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Then, in the stable matching that matches $x'$ to y (which must exist by the definition of the best match of $x'$ ), x and y would be an unstable pair, because y prefers x to $x'$ and x prefers y to any other partner in any stable matching.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] However, a stable matching cannot have an unstable pair.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] This contradiction shows that best matches are distinct, and therefore that assigning all doctors to their best matches gives a matching.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] It is a stable matching, because any unstable pair would also be unstable for one of the matchings used to define best matches.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] This matching, assigning all doctor to their best matches, also assigns all hospitals to their worst matches.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] In the partial ordering on stable matchings, it is greater than all other stable matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Symmetrically, assigning all doctors to their worst matches and assigning all hospitals to their best matches gives another stable matching.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] In the partial order on the matchings, it is less than all other stable matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] If the doctor is unemployed or has a less-preferred assignment, the doctor accepts the offer (and resigns from their other assignment if it exists).
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The process always terminates, because each doctor and hospital interact only once.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] When it terminates, the result is a stable matching, the one that assigns each hospital to its best match and that assigns all doctors to their worst matches.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Then both $P\vee Q$ and $P\wedge Q$ are matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Because the doctors are matched in $P\vee Q$ , the hospitals must also be matched.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The same reasoning applies symmetrically to $P\wedge Q$ .
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Additionally, both $P\vee Q$ and $P\wedge Q$ are stable.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] There cannot be a pair of a doctor and hospital who prefer each other to their match, because the same pair would necessarily also be an unstable pair for at least one of P and Q .
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The two operations $P\vee Q$ and $P\wedge Q$ form the join and meet operations of a finite distributive lattice.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] In the case of the operations $P\vee Q$ and $P\wedge Q$ defined above, the join $P\vee Q$ is greater than or equal to both P and Q because it was defined to give each doctor their preferred choice, and because these preferences of the doctors are how the ordering on matchings is defined.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] It is below any other matching that is also above both P and Q , because any such matching would have to give each doctor an assigned match that is at least as good.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Therefore, it fits the requirements for the join operation of a lattice.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Symmetrically, the operation $P\wedge Q$ fits the requirements for the meet operation.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Therefore, the lattice of stable matchings is a distributive lattice.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Birkhoff's representation theorem states that any finite distributive lattice can be represented by a family of finite sets, with intersection and union as the meet and join operations, and with the relation of being a subset as the comparison operation for the associated partial order.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] More specifically, these sets can be taken to be the lower sets of an associated partial order.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] In the general form of Birkhoff's theorem, this partial order can be taken as the induced order on a subset of the matchings in the lattice, the join-irreducible matchings (matchings that cannot be formed as joins of a subset of other matchings).
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] When a stable matching M is join-irreducible, let $M'$ be the join of the matchings below M in the partial order of stable matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Then $M'$ is not M , because it is a join of matchings distinct from M and M is not such a join. $M'$ is below M in the partial order of stable matchings, and there are no other stable matchings between $M'$ and M .
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] For the lattice of stable matchings, the partial order of Birkhoff's representation theorem can alternatively be described in terms of structures called *rotations*, first described in 1986 by Robert W.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Suppose that two different stable matchings P and Q are comparable and have no third stable matching between them in the partial order.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Another way of stating this is that P and Q form a pair of the covering relation of the partial order of stable matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] For instance, this is true for any join-irreducible matching M and the matching $M'$ formed by the join of the elements below M .
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Then the set of pairs of elements that are matched in one but not both of P and Q (the symmetric difference $P\oplus Q$ of their sets of matched pairs) is called a rotation.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] It forms a cycle graph whose edges alternate between matched pairs from P and from Q .
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Removing one of these two alternating sets of pairs, and adding the other alternating set, transforms P into Q or vice versa.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] More than one pair of matchings $(P,Q)$ and $(R,S)$ may define the same rotation $P\oplus Q=R\oplus S$ .
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] For any rotation, the top elements of pairs defining that rotation are closed under meet operations: if P and R are each the top matchings of pairs $(P,Q)$ and $(R,S)$ with $P\oplus Q=R\oplus S$ , then their meet $P\wedge R$ is also the top matching of another pair defining the same rotation.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] For every rotation, let M be the meet of all the top matchings of pairs defining that rotation.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Then M is join-irreducible, and the rotation is $M\oplus M'$ where $M'$ is the join of the matchings below M .
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] This gives a one-to-one correspondence between rotations and join-irreducible stable matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] If the rotations are given the same partial ordering as their corresponding join-irreducible stable matchings, then Birkhoff's representation theorem gives a one-to-one correspondence between lower sets of rotations and all stable matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The stable matching associated with any lower set of rotations can be obtained by applying the rotations to the bottom element of the lattice of stable matchings, choosing arbitrarily which rotation to apply when more than one can apply.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Because there are $n^{2}$ pairs of elements, there are $O(n^{2})$ rotations.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Beyond being a finite distributive lattice, there are no other constraints on the lattice structure of stable matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] This is because, for every finite distributive lattice L , there exists a stable matching instance whose lattice of stable matchings is isomorphic to L .
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] More strongly, if a finite distributive lattice has k elements, then it can be realized using a stable matching instance with at most $k^{2}-k+4$ doctors and hospitals.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The lattice of stable matchings can be used to study the computational complexity of counting the number of stable matchings of a given instance.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Computing the number of stable matchings is #P-complete.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] In a uniformly-random instance of the stable marriage problem with n doctors and n hospitals, the average number of stable matchings is asymptotically $e^{-1}n\ln n$ .
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] In a stable marriage instance chosen to maximize the number of different stable matchings, this number can be at least $2^{n-1}$ , and us also upper-bounded by an exponential function of n (significantly smaller than the naive factorial bound on the number of matchings).
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The family of rotations and their partial ordering can be constructed in polynomial time from a given instance of stable matching, and provides a concise representation to the family of all stable matchings, which can for some instances be exponentially larger when listed explicitly.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] This allows several other computations on stable matching instances to be performed efficiently.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] If each pair of participants in a stable matching instance is assigned a real-valued weight, it is possible to find the minimum or maximum weight stable matching in polynomial time.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] One possible method for this is to apply linear programming to the order polytope of the partial order of rotations, or to the stable matching polytope.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] An alternative, combinatorial algorithm is possible, based on the same partial order.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] By the correspondence between stable matchings and lower sets of rotations, the total weight of any matching is then equal to the total weight of its corresponding lower set, plus the weight of the bottom element of the lattice of matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The problem of finding the minimum or maximum weight stable matching becomes in this way equivalent to the problem of finding the minimum or maximum weight lower set in a partially ordered set of polynomial size, the partially ordered set of rotations.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] This optimal lower set problem is equivalent to an instance of the closure problem, a problem on vertex-weighted directed graphs in which the goal is to find a subset of vertices of optimal weight with no outgoing edges.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The optimal lower set is an optimal closure of a directed acyclic graph that has the elements of the partial order as its vertices, with an edge from $\alpha$ to $\beta$ whenever $\alpha \leq \beta$ in the partial order.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The closure problem can, in turn, be solved in polynomial time by transforming it into an instance of the maximum flow problem.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] Dan Gusfield has defined the *regret* of a participant in a stable matching to be the distance of their assigned match from the top of their preference list.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] He defines the regret of a stable matching to be the maximum regret of any participant.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] The elements of any distributive lattice form a median graph, a structure in which any three elements P , Q , and R (here, stable matchings) have a unique median element $m(P,Q,R)$ that lies on a shortest path between any two of them.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] For the lattice of stable matchings, this median can instead be taken element-wise, by assigning each doctor the median in the doctor's preferences of the three hospitals matched to that doctor in P , Q , and R and similarly by assigning each hospital the median of the three doctors matched to it.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] More generally, any set of an odd number of elements of any distributive lattice (or median graph) has a median, a unique element minimizing its sum of distances to the given set.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] For the median of an odd number of stable matchings, each participant is matched to the median element of the multiset of their matches from the given matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] For an even set of stable matchings, this can be disambiguated by choosing the assignment that matches each doctor to the higher of the two median elements, and each hospital to the lower of the two median elements.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] In particular, this leads to a definition for the median matching in the set of all stable matchings.
[src:stable-roommates/lattice-of-stable-matchings] However, for some instances of the stable matching problem, finding this median of all stable matchings is NP-hard.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] The **National Resident Matching Program** (**NRMP**), also called **The Match**, is a United States–based private non-profit non-governmental organization created in 1952 to place U.S. medical school students into residency training programs located in United States teaching hospitals.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Its mission has since expanded to include the placement of U.S. citizen and non-U.S. citizen international medical school students and graduates into residency and fellowship training programs.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In addition to the annual Main Residency Match that in 2021 encompassed more than 48,000 applicants and 38,000 positions, the NRMP conducts Fellowship Matches for more than 60 subspecialties through its Specialties Matching Service (SMS).
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] The NRMP is sponsored by a board of directors that includes medical school deans, teaching hospital executives, graduate medical education program directors, medical students and residents, and one public member.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] NRMP International, a subsidiary of the National Resident Matching Program, was established in 2010 to provide medical matching services outside the United States and Canada.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] The combination of those factors led to offers being made for positions up to two years in advance of the start of postgraduate training.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In 1945, medical schools decided not to release any transcripts or permit any letters of recommendation to be written until a particular date.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In that way, they managed to move the date of residency selection back to the fourth year of medical school.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] However, the competition for residents simply took on another form.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Programs began to issue offers with a time limit for reply.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] The time limit rapidly decreased from 10 days in 1945 to less than 12 hours in 1950.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Students were being issued "exploding" offers that required them to make a decision about training before hanging up the telephone.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In the early 1950s, the National Interassociation Committee on Internships (NICI) examined existing matching plans and chose the Boston Pool Plan, utilized at the time by Boston-area programs, as the model for a trial run of a new centralized system.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In October 1951, student representatives from 79 medical schools formed the National Student Internship Committee (NSIC) to discuss the findings of the NICI trial Match and consider an NICI proposal to replicate the Boston Pool Plan at the national level.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] NSIC petitioned to have the algorithm modified to more equitably represent applicants, and the modified algorithm was adopted and used for the first Match on 1952.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] That Match was a success, and the NICI recommended the creation of an organization to administer and oversee the running of the Match.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] The organization, known as the National Intern Matching Program (NIMP), was established in 1952 at the request of medical students.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Modifications to the algorithm proposed by students in 1951 were based on concerns that the matching process favored hospitals over applicants.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] The students believed the algorithm gave them incentives to misrepresent their true preferences.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] A publication in 1962 by David Gale & Lloyd Shapley noted that there always exists a stable solution when colleges are matching with students, but that it is possible to favor colleges as a group over applicants as a group (and vice versa).
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] That is, Gale and Shapley found that there is a college-optimal stable match and an applicant-optimal stable match.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Lloyd Shapley along with Alvin Roth, would go on to win the 2012 Nobel Prize in Economics for their work on stable allocations.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] A debate arose regarding whether the matching program was susceptible to manipulation or unreasonably fair to programs.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Indeed, it was shown that in simple cases (i.e. those that exclude couples, second-year programs, and special cases for handling unfilled slots) that had multiple "stable" matchings, the algorithm would return the solution that preferred the preferences of programs over applicants.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] A correspondence in *New England Journal of Medicine* in 1981 recognized that the algorithm in use was program-optimal for individual applicants.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Later researchers, such as Marilda Sotomayor in 1983, Alvin Roth in 1984, and Klaus et al. in 2007, found that when couples are allowed to match together, there may exist no stable matching.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] However, Fuhito Kojima and Parag Pathak in 2009 demonstrated that if the market is large and the fraction of couples is small, then a stable matching exists with high probability.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] The NRMP algorithm saw only minor and incremental changes after its institution in 1952.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] However, in the fall of 1995 the NRMP Board of Directors commissioned a preliminary research study to evaluate the current algorithm and recommend changes to be considered in its operation and description, as well as a study comparing a new algorithm with the existing one.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] A new applicant-proposing algorithm was adopted in May 1997 and has been in use since its first application in March 1998, although the study showed that the net effect of the change on actual matches has been minimal.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Matching applicants to programs is a generalization of the stable marriage problem; as a result, the solutions are very similar.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] A simplified version of the algorithm that is used to perform the matching process is described below and on the NRMP website.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] However, this description does not include the handling of couples (pairs of applicants who participate in a Match together, perhaps to stay in the same geographic location), second-year positions, or special handling of residency positions that remain unfilled.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] The full algorithm is described in Roth & Peranson 1999.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] The application process for residency training begins prior to the opening of the Main Residency Match in September.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Applications usually are sent to programs through the Electronic Residency Application Service (ERAS), a service of the Association of American Medical Colleges.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] After applicants apply to programs, programs review applications and invite selected candidates for interviews held between October and February.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] After the interview period is over, programs and applicants each compile "rank order lists" that they submit to the NRMP.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Programs list applicants, ranked in order from most to least preferred, whom they wish to train.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Similarly, applicants rank programs where they wish to train.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] For applicants matching as a couple, the rank order lists include pairs of program choices that are considered simultaneously by the matching algorithm.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] For advanced programs on the rank order list, applicants can append a supplemental list of preliminary programs to attempt to match to a full course of training.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] The matching process begins with an attempt to match an applicant to the program most preferred on that applicant's rank order list (ROL).
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] This process is carried out for all applicants until each applicant has either been tentatively matched to the most preferred choice possible or all choices submitted by all applicants have been exhausted.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] To understand how the current NRMP algorithm works, it is helpful to begin by considering the simpler case where there are no couples or secondary programs.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] As in the stable marriage problem, the basic goal is to match applicants to programs so that the results are "stable".
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] It can be shown that for any instance of the problem, there is at least one valid solution.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Under the old (pre-1995) NRMP algorithm that favored programs' preferences over applicants', programs could benefit in certain cases from lying about their preferences.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] This is no longer possible under the current algorithm.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Applicants cannot benefit by lying about their preferences, even if they have perfect knowledge of everyone's preferences.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Under the current system, it also is impossible for an applicant to be harmed by including more residency programs at the bottom of a list if those programs are indeed preferable to not being matched.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Couples' rank order lists are processed simultaneously by the matching algorithm, which complicates the problem.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In some cases there exists no stable solution (with stable defined the way it is in the simple case).
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In fact, the problem of determining whether there is a stable solution and finding it if it exists has been proven NP-complete.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Also, while there is no randomization in the NRMP algorithm—so it will always return the same output when given exactly the same input—different outcomes can be produced by changing trivial features of the data such as the order in which applicants and programs are processed.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] However, in initial testing of the algorithm over 5 years of residency match data and a variety of different initial conditions, the current NRMP algorithm always terminated quickly on a stable solution.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Testing also showed that "none of [the trivial] sequencing decisions had a large or systematic effect on the matching produced"—the maximum number of applicants ever observed to be affected in a single run was 12 out of 22,938.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In general *once the programs' rank order lists have been set*, there is no way for an applicant to match into a better position by deciding to match as part of a couple.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] For example, if a very strong applicant and a very weak applicant match as a couple, there is no mechanism *in the algorithm* that allows the stronger applicant to somehow improve the desirability of the weaker applicant.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] It is possible for an applicant not to match to a program.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Until the 2010 Main Residency Match, applicants who did not obtain a position went through a process called the Scramble.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] At 12:00 p.m. on Monday of Match Week, the NRMP notified applicants whether they had matched to a program (but did not release the name of the program) and released a list of unfilled programs.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Applicants then applied en masse to programs that had unfilled positions, frequently having to change their preferred specialty in the process.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] The Scramble was widely recognized to be chaotic, disorganized, and lacking in transparency.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] The Scramble ended on Match Day, which was Thursday of Match Week.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Most positions filled within the first few hours, and nearly all in the first 48 hours.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Scrambling was extremely competitive: in 2008, roughly 10,600 applicants, many of whom were foreign-trained, scrambled for only 1,392 residency positions.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] After the 2010 Main Residency Match, the Scramble was replaced by the Supplemental Offer and Acceptance Program, or SOAP.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In SOAP, unmatched applicants are offered positions in unfilled programs through a series of rounds, creating a systematic way for applicants to find training positions without the chaos of the Scramble.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In SOAP, all appointments are made through the NRMP (no direct matching allowed, unlike the Scramble), and unmatched applicant data and unfilled program data are released at the same time on Monday of Match Week.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Of the 35,476 total active applicants who participated in The National Resident Matching Program in 2016, 75.6% (26,836) were able to find PGY-1 (R-1) matches.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Out of the total active applicants, 51.27% (18,187) were graduates of conventional US medical schools; 93.8% (17,057) were able to find a match.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In comparison, match rates were 80.3% of osteopathic graduates, 53.9% of US citizen international medical school graduates, and 50.5% of non-US citizen international medical schools graduates.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In 2021, there were a total of 48,700 registered applicants.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] A total of 38,106 positions were offered in the match.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] MD seniors matched to PGY1 positions, while the percentage for U.S.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] To participate in the NRMP, an international medical graduate must have ECFMG ID.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] USMLE ID is not required for IMGs, but it can be entered.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] IMGs must not be completely ECFMG certified but most programs require USMLE Step 2 before "Rank Order List Submission Deadline".
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Many programs require ECFMG certificate submitted with the initial application.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In comparison, students and graduates from medical schools in the United States are bound to the graduation requirements of their individual schools.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Both U.S. and foreign-trained applicants can participate in the NRMP while completing their final year of medical school before acquiring their medical diplomas.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In 2002, 16 law firms filed a lawsuit on behalf of three residents seeking to represent all residents matching through the NRMP.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] The plaintiffs put forward a case which sought to show that the NRMP colluded with other national medical and medical education organizations and with residency-sponsoring institutions to depress resident wages, operating in violation of United States antitrust legislation.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] In 2004, after a lobbying effort by the Association of American Medical Colleges and the American Hospital Association, a rider that granted specific immunity to the NRMP was added to a pension act signed into law by President George W.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] The provision was sponsored by Senators Edward M.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Kennedy, Democrat of Massachusetts, and Judd Gregg, Republican of New Hampshire.
[src:stable-roommates/national-resident-matching-program] Subsequently, a federal district court dismissed the case.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] In mathematics, economics, and computer science, the **stable matching problem** is the problem of finding a stable matching between two equally sized sets of elements given an ordering of preferences for each element.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] A matching is a bijection from the elements of one set to the elements of the other set.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] In other words, a matching is stable when there does not exist any pair (*A*, *B*) which both prefer each other to their current partner under the matching.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] The existence of two classes that need to be paired with each other (heterosexual men and women in this example) distinguishes this problem from the stable roommates problem.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] Algorithms for finding solutions to the stable marriage problem have applications in a variety of real-world situations, perhaps the best known of these being in the assignment of graduating medical students to their first hospital appointments.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] In 2012, the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences was awarded to Lloyd S.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] An extension of the Gale-Shapley algorithm has been used in content delivery networks.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] Optimizing performance from a user's point of view and balancing server load requires a good matching of clusters of users accessing a given type of content (e.g. web pages or video) with clusters of servers well-positioned to serve them the desired content.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] This can be modeled as user clusters and server clusters having (partial) preferences over each other based on variables such as network topology or contractual agreements with internet service providers.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] This can then be solved as a stable matching problem.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] A generalization of the classic Gale-Shapley approach is necessary because there are unequal numbers of clusters on each side, because demand and capacity can vary between clusters, and because the preferences are partial instead of total.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] The Gale–Shapley algorithm for stable matching is used to assign rabbis who graduate from Hebrew Union College to Jewish congregations.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] All three are stable, because instability requires both of the participants to be happier with an alternative match.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] Giving one group their first choices ensures that the matches are stable because they would be unhappy with any other proposed match.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] Giving everyone their second choice ensures that any other match would be disliked by one of the parties.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] In general, the family of solutions to any instance of the stable marriage problem can be given the structure of a finite distributive lattice, and this structure leads to efficient algorithms for several problems on stable marriages.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] In a uniformly-random instance of the stable marriage problem with n men and n women, the average number of stable matchings is asymptotically $e^{-1}n\ln n$ .
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] In a stable marriage instance chosen to maximize the number of different stable matchings, this number is an exponential function of n.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] Counting the number of stable matchings in a given instance is #P-complete.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] In 1962, David Gale and Lloyd Shapley proved that, for any equal number in different groups, in the context of college admissions and individuals wanting marriage it is always possible to solve as matched couples to make all resultant pairings / matched factors stable.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] This algorithm is guaranteed to produce a stable marriage for all participants in time $O(n^{2})$ where n is the number of men or women.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] Among all possible different stable matchings, it always yields the one that is best for all men among all stable matchings, and worst for all women.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] It is a truthful mechanism from the point of view of men (the proposing side), i.e., no man can get a better matching for himself by misrepresenting his preferences.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] Moreover, the GS algorithm is even *group-strategy proof* for men, i.e., no coalition of men can coordinate a misrepresentation of their preferences such that all men in the coalition are strictly better-off.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] However, it is possible for some coalition to misrepresent their preferences such that some men are better-off and the other men retain the same partner.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] The GS algorithm is non-truthful for the women (the reviewing side): each woman may be able to misrepresent her preferences and get a better match.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] The Gale–Shapley algorithm also exposes parallelism for accelerating large-scale SMP instances, since unengaged men can make proposals independently in each round.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] Parallel implementations can assign men to different threads, resolve simultaneous proposals with synchronization primitives, and use optimizations such as queue avoidance, locality-aware data layouts, and hybrid CPU–GPU execution to reduce overhead.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] In this case, the condition of stability is that no unmatched pair prefer each other to their situation in the matching (whether that situation is another partner or being unmatched).
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] With this condition, a stable matching will still exist, and can still be found by the Gale–Shapley algorithm.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] In **stable matching with indifference**, some men might be indifferent between two or more women and vice versa.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] The **stable roommates problem** is similar to the stable marriage problem, but differs in that all participants belong to a single pool (instead of being divided into equal numbers of "men" and "women").
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] The **hospitals/residents problem** – also known as the **college admissions problem** – differs from the stable marriage problem in that a hospital can take multiple residents, or a college can take an incoming class of more than one student.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] Algorithms to solve the hospitals/residents problem can be *hospital-oriented* (as the NRMP was before 1995) or *resident-oriented*.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] This problem was solved, with an algorithm, in the same original paper by Gale and Shapley, in which the stable marriage problem was solved.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] The addition of couples to the hospitals/residents problem renders the problem NP-complete.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] The **assignment problem** seeks to find a matching in a weighted bipartite graph that has maximum weight.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] Maximum weighted matchings do not have to be stable, but in some applications a maximum weighted matching is better than a stable one.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] The **matching with contracts** problem is a generalization of matching problem, in which participants can be matched with different terms of contracts.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] An important special case of contracts is matching with flexible wages.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] The **popular matching problem** seeks a matching $M^{*}$ such that no other matching M exists with more people happier with M than with $M^{*}$ .
[src:stable-roommates/stable-marriage-problem] For non-bipartite inputs, it is NP-complete to determine whether a popular matching exists.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] In mathematics, economics and computer science, particularly in the fields of combinatorial game theory and algorithms, the **stable-roommate problem** (**SRP**) is the problem of finding a **stable matching** for an even-sized set.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] A matching is a separation of the set into disjoint pairs ("roommates").
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] The matching is *stable* if there are no two elements which are not roommates and which both prefer each other to their roommate under the matching.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] This is distinct from the stable matching problem (stable-marriage problem) in that the stable-roommates problem allows matches between any two elements, not only between classes of *men* and *women*.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] participants ranks the others in strict order of preference.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] Unlike the stable marriage problem, a stable matching may fail to exist for certain sets of participants and their preferences.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] In this ranking, each of A, B, and C is the most preferable person for someone.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] In any solution, one of A, B, or C *must* be paired with D and the other two with each other (for example AD and BC), yet for anyone who is partnered with D, another member will have rated them highest, and D's partner will in turn prefer this other member over D.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] In this example, AC is a more favorable pairing than AD, but the necessary remaining pairing of BD then raises the same issue, illustrating the absence of a stable matching for these participants and their preferences.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] An efficient algorithm (Irving 1985) is the following.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] The algorithm will determine, for any instance of the problem, whether a stable matching exists, and if so, will find such a matching.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] Irving's algorithm has O(*n*2) complexity, provided suitable data structures are used to implement the necessary manipulation of the preference lists and identification of rotations.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] In Phase 1, participants *propose* to each other, in a manner similar to that of the Gale–Shapley algorithm for the stable marriage problem.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] Each participant orders the other members by preference, resulting in a preference list—an ordered set of the other participants.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] Participants then propose to each person on their list, in order, continuing to the next person if and when their current proposal is rejected.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] A participant will reject a proposal if they already hold a proposal from someone they prefer.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] A participant will also reject a previously-accepted proposal if they later receive a proposal that they prefer.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] In this case, the rejected participant will then propose to the next person on their list, continuing until a proposal is again accepted.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] If any participant is eventually rejected by all other participants, this indicates that no stable matching is possible.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] Otherwise, Phase 1 will end with each person holding a proposal from one of the others.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] The resulting reduced set of preference lists together is called the Phase 1 table.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] In this table, if any reduced list is empty, then there is no stable matching.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] Otherwise, the Phase 1 table is a *stable table*.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] In any stable table, if every reduced list contains *exactly* one individual, then pairing each individual with the single person on their list gives a stable matching.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] If the stable roommates problem instance has a stable matching, then there is a stable matching contained in any one of the stable tables.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] Any stable subtable of a stable table, and in particular any stable subtable that specifies a stable matching as in 2, can be obtained by a sequence of *rotation eliminations* on the stable table.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] These rotation eliminations comprise Phase 2 of Irving's algorithm.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] By 2, if each reduced list of the Phase 1 table contains exactly one individual, then this gives a matching.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] Otherwise, the algorithm enters Phase 2.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] It follows that in any stable table with a reduced list containing at least two individuals, such a rotation always exists.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] The sequence of *p*i up until the *p*j is called the *tail* of the rotation.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] The fact that it's a stable table in which this search occurs guarantees that each *p*i has at least two individuals on their list.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] To eliminate the rotation, *y*i rejects *x*i so that *x*i proposes to *y*i+1, for each *i*.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] To restore the stable table properties (i) and (ii), for each *i*, all successors of *x*i-1 are removed from *y*i's list, and *y*i is removed from their lists.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] If a reduced list becomes empty during these removals, then there is no stable matching.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] Otherwise, the new table is again a stable table, and either already specifies a matching since each list contains exactly one individual or there remains another rotation to find and eliminate, so the step is repeated.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] To achieve an O(*n*2) running time, a ranking matrix whose entry at row *i* and column *j* is the position of the *j*th individual in the *i*th's list; this takes O(*n*2) time.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] With the ranking matrix, checking whether an individual prefers one to another can be done in constant time by comparing their ranks in the matrix.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] Furthermore, instead of explicitly removing elements from the preference lists, the indices of the first, second and last on each individual's reduced list are maintained.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] The first individual that is *unmatched*, i.e. has at least two in their reduced lists, is also maintained.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] Then, in Phase 2, the sequence of *p*i "traversed" to find a rotation is stored in a list, and an array is used to mark individuals as having been visited, as in a standard depth-first search graph traversal.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] After the elimination of a rotation, we continue to store only its tail, if any, in the list and as visited in the array, and start the search for the next rotation at the last individual on the tail, and otherwise at the next unmatched individual if there is no tail.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] This reduces repeated traversal of the tail, since it is largely unaffected by the elimination of the rotation.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] The following are the preference lists for a Stable Roommates instance involving 6 participants: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] A possible execution of Phase 1 consists of the following sequence of proposals and rejections, where → represents *proposes to* and × represents *rejects*.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] In Phase 2, the rotation *r*1 = (1,4), (3,2) is first identified.
[src:stable-roommates/stable-roommates-problem] This is because 2 is 1's second favorite, and 4 is the second favorite of 3.
